Cosine Similarity Search using Qdrant
Introduction

This project demonstrates how semantic search works using vector embeddings and the Qdrant Vector Database. Instead of searching using exact keywords, the system compares vector representations of text to retrieve the most relevant information.

Working

The application first reads all text chunks from a text file.

Each chunk is converted into a numerical vector using the SentenceTransformer embedding model.

These vectors are stored inside a Qdrant collection.

When a user enters a query:

The query is converted into a vector.
Qdrant compares the query vector with all stored vectors using cosine similarity.
The Top-5 most similar vectors are retrieved.
The original text associated with those vectors is displayed.
Components Used
Python
SentenceTransformer
Qdrant
Docker
Cosine Similarity
Applications
AI Chatbots
Legal AI
Document Search
Medical Search Systems
Enterprise Knowledge Bases
Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)
Learning Outcome

Through this project, I learned:

How embeddings represent text.
How vector databases store embeddings.
How cosine similarity performs semantic search.
How retrieved chunks form the retrieval stage of a RAG system.